N2 adsorption/desorption isotherms were performed to investigate the surface areas and pore size distributions of the materials (Fig. 6
                        ). It can be observed from Fig. 6 that the pure BiOI nanocatellite exhibits a significant H3 curve model, which attributes to the sheet-like structure being in agreement with the result in literature [10]. However, the amino functionalized H-mSiO2 and the loaded H-mSiO2-BiOI and H-mSiO2-BiOI/CQDs materials all exhibit an H1 isothermal curve model, ascribing to open ends of cylindrical hole with the same diameter, which is in agreement with the ordered mesoporous structure of H-mSiO2 
                        [63].

In an attempt to elucidate the photocatalytic mechanism involved in the photodegradation of RhB by H-mSiO2-BiOI/CQDs materials, a series of photo-degradation experiments with the addition of different scavengers were carried out. It is well known that holes (h+), super oxygen free radicals (O2
                        •−), and hydroxyl radicals (•OH) and e− are the main reactive species and trigger the oxidation of organic pollutants. The absorption peak value of RhB at 553 nm analyzed by UV–vis spectrophotometer could indirectly reflect the degradation efficiency after being illuminated for 40 min (Fig. 14
                        ).
